<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-05-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-05-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="1033" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1033">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 125.8273/38d.</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the <gloss type="to">Brazilian Minister at Mexico
                                        City</gloss>.</hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                        <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-05-05">
                                        <hi rend="italic">May 5, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>The Department is in receipt of a telegram from the American Consul
                                General at Monterey stating that Vice Consul Silliman is in prison
                                at Saltillo, together with several other American citizens. Please
                                bring this to the attention of the appropriate authorities at once
                                and represent in the strongest possible manner the necessity for
                                immediate action. There can be no possible excuse for the
                                imprisonment of this officer except political antipathy on the part
                                of those responsible for his arrest. The Consul General at Monterey
                                was himself imprisoned for several days prior to the occupation of
                                that <pb facs="0778" n="662" xml:id="pg_662"/> city and he was only
                                released when the Constitutionalists took possession of the city.
                                Please insist on immediate action.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">W. J. Bryan</hi></signed>.</closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>